Effects of group_by
Operations do not have to select only a single row like slice_max

To get “above average” penguins for each species

penguins |&gt; 
    group_by(species) |&gt; 
    filter(body_mass_g &gt; mean(body_mass_g, na.rm=TRUE))

Stopping groups
Once you are done with grouped operations, ungroup

penguins |&gt; 
    group_by(species, island) |&gt;
    slice_max(body_mass_g) |&gt;
    ungroup()

# A tibble: 5 × 8
  species   island    bill_length_mm bill_depth_mm flipper_length_mm body_mass_g
  &lt;fct&gt;     &lt;fct&gt;              &lt;dbl&gt;         &lt;dbl&gt;             &lt;int&gt;       &lt;int&gt;
1 Adelie    Biscoe              43.2          19                 197        4775
2 Adelie    Dream               39.8          19.1               184        4650
3 Adelie    Torgersen           42.9          17.6               196        4700
4 Chinstrap Dream               52            20.7               210        4800
5 Gentoo    Biscoe              49.2          15.2               221        6300
# ℹ 2 more variables: sex &lt;fct&gt;, year &lt;int&gt;

Numeric Variables
Better choices:

Group on quantiles (ntile) or cut points (cut)


penguins |&gt;
    mutate(mass_5ile = ntile(body_mass_g, 5)) |&gt;
    group_by(mass_5ile) |&gt;
    ...

mutate
Can change columns “in place” by careful renaming:

penguins |&gt; 
    select(where(is.character) | where(is.factor)) |&gt;
    mutate(species = toupper(species)) |&gt;
    slice_head(n=5)

# A tibble: 5 × 3
  species island    sex   
  &lt;chr&gt;   &lt;fct&gt;     &lt;fct&gt; 
1 ADELIE  Torgersen male  
2 ADELIE  Torgersen female
3 ADELIE  Torgersen female
4 ADELIE  Torgersen &lt;NA&gt;  
5 ADELIE  Torgersen female



Use this sparingly - destroys ‘original’ values

