Nesting requires multiple indents:

x = 100
if x &gt; 0:
    print("x is positive")

    if x &gt;= 100: 
        print("x has three digits")
else:
    print("x is negative")

x is positive
x has three digits

python provides an elif where in R we used else if:

x = 0
if x &gt; 0:
    print("x is positive")
elif x &lt; 0:
    print("x is negative")
else: 
    print("x is zero")

x is zero


Neither elif or else are required, but else must be last

Common to use None (roughly equivalent to R NULL) for ‘missing’-type default values

def say_hello(name, message = None):
    if message: 
        print("Hello", name, "!", message)
    else: 
        print("Hello", name, "!")

say_hello("Michael")

Hello Michael !

say_hello("Michael", "Welcome to STA 9750!")

Hello Michael ! Welcome to STA 9750!

Subclasses

class BassetHound(Dog):
    breed = "Basset Hound"

    def bark(self, n=1): 
        return "Arooo!" * n

class Basenji(Dog):
    breed = "Basenji"

    def bark(self, n=1):
        return ""

class Collie(Dog):
    breed = "Collie"

Methods vs Functions
Unlike R, python objects can be changed “in place”:

class BankAccount:
    def __init__(self, initial_balance=0):
        self._balance = initial_balance

    def deposit(self, deposit_amount):
        self._balance += deposit_amount

    def withdraw(self, withdraw_amount):
        self._balance -= withdraw_amount

    def balance(self):
        return self._balance

    def __repr__(self):
        return f"BankAccount({self._balance})"

Defining Classes
You can define a class with a class statement:

class Dog:
    def __init__(self, name, owner):
        self.name = name
        self.owner = owner

    def __repr__(self):
        return f"Dog(name='{self.name}', owner='{self.owner}')"

    def bark(self, n=1):
        return "Woof!" * n

One regular method (bark)

All methods take self as the first object

